[5] Cholera - Papua New Guinea (Western province)
Date: Fri 26 Nov 2010
Source: The Age (Australia) [edited]
<http://www.theage.com.au/national/cholera-outbreak-spreads-to-png-20101125=-1895s.html>


An outbreak of cholera in the Torres Strait has spread to scores of
island and coastal villages in the Fly River delta area of Papua New
Guinea's [PNG] Western Province, killing more than 100 people and
infecting hundreds of others.

The disease had already killed 32 people and infected 888 others on
Daru, the most highly populated island in the Torres Strait. Many of
the victims are children.

Ian Kemish, Australia's high commissioner in Port Moresby, told The
Age the new outbreak is much harder to handle than on Daru because it
is in remote areas where there is poor communication, difficult
travel conditions, and widely dispersed villages.

Mr Kemish, who led a delegation of foreign officials to Daru island,
said the situation among the 21 000 population there was now
"relatively stable".

"There have been 2 deaths on the island since last week compared to 2
or 3 deaths a day when the disease broke out," he said.

Australia closed the Torres Strait border with PNG 3 weeks ago as a
precaution against the spread of the disease into Queensland. Since
10 Nov 2010, 314 PNG nationals who traveled across the border into
Australian territory have been turned back. Normally, traditional
visits to Australia by indigenous inhabitants are allowed under
free-movement provisions of the Torres Strait Treaty. The latest
restrictions do not apply to other travelers, including those holding
passports and visas.

Australian officials say the restriction will remain in place until
further notice, but will be subject to ongoing review. They say the
border was closed in consultation with PNG authorities in Daru, which
is 4 km [2.5 mi] from the PNG mainland and 50 km [31 mi] from the
nearest Australian island.

[Byline: Lindsay Murdoch]

